transcription.commentary: Since the cognomen Censorinus is not followed by a statement of rank but by [pro] salute sua it can hardly represent the official style of a praefectus equitum stated to be in command of (cui praeest) the ala Tungrorum. It must then presumably represent a personal dedication by an individual for his own welfare. In this case ala tvvp can hardly represent ala Tungrorum, but may conceal a divine name, for example Alateiviae (CIL xiii 8606), one of the titles of the Matres. A German title of this kind is not inappropriate at Burgh-by-Sands, where the coh. I Nervana Germanorum (see RIB 2041) was stationed R. P. W.

transcription.commentary: See also RIB 1327, 1328.2-4. Optimi Maximique Imperatores: probably Marcus Aurelius with Commodus a.d. 177-180 (PIR¹ V no. 557).4-5. Ulp(io) Marcello: consular governor of Britain, a.d. 177-84.The shrine containing these two altars (RIB 1327 and 1329), demolished when they were overturned, contained no coin later than Marcus Aurelius and was therefore presumably destroyed in a.d. 197 (). In this case the joint emperors must be Marcus Aurelius and Commodus (see ). This will carry the governorship of Ulpius Marcellus back at least to the autumn of a.d. 180 as quaestors were designated for the forthcoming December on 23 January ().Although Birley (in Askew Coinage 81 no. 31) cites as evidence for an unknown governor in a.d. 181, Dio's phrase στρατηγόν τινα μετὰ τῶν στρατιωτῶν κατακοψάντων is more likely to refer to a less important officer, probably a legionary legate.Ulpius Marcellus is now attested as governor of Britain on 23 March 178 (and by implication since at least 177) under two Emperors, Marcus Aurelius and Commodus: the evidence is a new military diploma published by , who discusses the problem raised by , that Marcellus was still (or once again) governor of Britain in 184. See also Birley Altar dedicated to Anociticus, 140-2, 164-6, where the hypothesis of a second Ulpius Marcellus must now be abandoned.

eagleObject.description: Upper portion in three fragments, broken horizontally through the first line. In a niche with flattened gable a cavalry-man gallops to right. His horse is of mettle, with small high-bred head, on which a head-stall is visible, while a saddle-cloth covers a horizontal strap. The mane is well groomed and the tail is long and flowing. The rider brandishes a weapon, probably a sword, in his right hand, while his left holds a long oval shield, mostly hidden behind the horse's head. His clothing seems to comprise a mailed tunic and mailed breeches to the knee. His head is defaced. Below the horse a naked barbarian lies prone, clasping a large oblong shield. No other weapon is visible.

transcription.commentary: The top has two dowel-holes, 1.27 cm in diam., for a statuette, and on the rounded edge at a point midway between the holes there is the letter l, 1.59 cm high, inlaid in a silver alloy.Macdonald suggests that l stands for l(egionis) (for this abbreviation see CIL vi 37213 (ILS 2044), CIL x 18, ILS 2232), and that if the statuette was that of Victory, it might have been necessary to differentiate the Victoria l(egionis) from the Victoria Aug. It must, however, be observed that in these cases the number of the legion accompanies l and thus puts the interpretation beyond doubt. His further suggestion that this base may possibly have belonged to the silver statuette of Victory of which the arm was discovered on Tunshill Farm, in the parish of Milnrow, Lancs., RIB 582, still requires the further proof which he desired R. P. W.

transcription.commentary: 2, 3. Birley, loc. cit., points out that Camden may have recorded the text inaccurately but that, on the basis of the recorded text, it can best be explained as a military appointment. The civilian title senator was mainly confined to the Roman senate and from the middle of the second century this rank was expressed by v(ir) c(larissimus). In the fourth century senator could express a non-commissioned rank in the army (ILS 2796, n. 1 quoting Jerome, ), and to explain questorio there is a military instance of quaestor on an inscription of a.d. 186, CIL iii 1396 (ILS 2630). Birley therefore interprets the phrase in a military sense: sen(atori) in c(ohorte) Carvetior(um), questorio.Nevertheless, a civilian interpretation is not to be excluded. In a few instances in fourth- and fifth-century documents [Ausonius Mosella 402. Cod. Theod. xii i 85 (a.d. 381), Novellae Maioriani vii i (a.d. 457-61) curiales … quorum coetum recte appellavit antiquitas minorem senatum] senatus or senator is applied to local towns, and questorius would accord well with this. The expansion might then be: sen(atori) in c(ivitate) Carvetior(um). This civitas is elsewhere unattested, but on the basis of the mileage quoted on the Middleton milestone (RIB 2283) C. E. Stevens (EHR lii (1937) 200) suggests the possibility that Carlisle was the civitas Carvetiorum.
